  "text": "The alerting evaluation scheduler tick is implemented across three key files:\n\n1. **`pkg/services/ngalert/schedule/ticker/ticker.go`**: Defines the `T` struct (a custom ticker) and its `run()` goroutine. The ticker emits ticks on fixed interval marks via a channel `C`, never dropping ticks — instead queuing them so the consumer can detect overruns.\n\n2. **`pkg/services/ngalert/schedule/schedule.go`**: Contains the main scheduling loop:\n   - `schedulePeriodic()` (line 246): reads ticks from `ticker.T.C` and calls `processTick()`. It records `BehindSeconds` metric (line 256) to measure how far behind the scheduler is relative to the tick time — an implicit overrun indicator.\n   - `processTick()` (line 276): determines which alert rules are due for evaluation on the current tick, dispatches them via `runJobFn`.\n   - `runJobFn()` (line 426): sends each scheduled evaluation to the rule's evaluation goroutine via `alertRule.Eval()`. When `Eval()` returns a non-nil `dropped` value, it means a previous tick was still queued (the rule evaluation is too slow to keep up), and this function logs the overrun: `sch.log.Warn(\"Tick dropped because alert rule evaluation is too slow\", ...)` and increments the `EvaluationMissed` counter metric.\n\n3. **`pkg/services/ngalert/schedule/alert_rule.go`**: Implements `alertRule.Eval()` (line 200): uses a buffered channel (`evalCh`) of capacity 1. Before sending a new tick, it does a non-blocking read of the channel. If there is already a pending evaluation (i.e., the previous tick has not been consumed yet), it returns that as the `droppedMsg`. This is how the cycle overrun is detected at the rule level and surfaced back to `runJobFn` in `schedule.go` for logging."
}

